reviewText: This is a review that is long overdo. I've been enjoying the great pizza at this restaurant for over a year now and it's hands down the best in town. I saw a review on here saying the pizza was greasy, and I'll bet it was for a peperoni pizza. I don't know how you could put so many slices of peperoni on, where you can't even see the cheese, without a little pepperoni grease escaping. These guys at Firehouse make the pizzas that everyone else does in their commercials, you can watch as they pile the toppings a mile high on every pie. And when was the last time you saw someone slicing bell peppers and tomatoes by hand for your pizza. I honestly have a hard time understanding how these guys stay in business, but I'm glad they do. And the five dollar slice and soda lunch is probably the best value in town. Thanks guys, keep it up.

reviewText: The Rocking V does rock.  Attentive, expert servers are friendly and welcoming.  The menu and specials are both creative and satisfying for a wide range of tastes from Vegan to Carnivore. Beautiful presentation.  You could be in the most expensive San Francisco restaurant and have dishes from the Rocking V placed before you and not a thing would be out of place.  The quality is right on par.  It is just more fun in Kanab.  Even the art on their gallery walls is a plus...rare in smaller towns.  By the time you finish dinner, you feel a part of this establishment, or it becomes a part of you. The place to eat in Utah, certainly the place to eat in Kanab.

reviewText: Sí que es verdad que es uno de los sitios más emblemáticos de la ciudad, un restaurante  con solera e historia, pero el precio me parece elevado para lo que ofrece. Al final, uno paga más por lo que es que por lo que come. Eso sí, si quieres quedar bien con una visita de fuera, pide el cochinillo asado, que triunfas seguro.
name: Botín
translated: Yes, it is true that it is one of the most emblematic places in the city, a restaurant with tradition and history, but the price seems high for what it offers. In the end, you pay more for what you are than for what you eat. Of course, if you want to look good with a visitor from outside, order the roast suckling pig, which is sure to be a success.

reviewText: Un sitio ideal para ir con tu pareja o alguien cercano y sorprenderlo. El sitio es pequeño, con lo que no recomiendo ir con mucha gente. Además, debido a su popularidad y a su buen hacer en la cocina, suele haber colas grandes, así que es mejor reservar con antelación. Muy bien de precios y mejor de sabores (sobre todo el chocolate con pétalos de rosa).
name: El Jardín Secreto
translated: An ideal place to go with your partner or someone close and surprise them. The place is small, so I don't recommend going with many people. Also, due to its popularity and its good work in the kitchen, there are usually long queues, so it is best to book in advance. Very good prices and better flavors (especially the chocolate with rose petals).

reviewText: Have been going to this restaurant for years and always enjoyed fresh sliced turkey dinner with the sides and pie for dessert for a reasonable price.  On this Thanksgiving Day all four in our party ordered the above but received pressed turkey, cold and uncooked yams served in little cut up squares, uncooked veggies.  It was terrible and we sent it back and ordered the fresh cut ham but it was canned ham and the sides were the same as above.  They would not allow us to order from the regular menu and the charge for this terrible dinner was $24.95 each.  The apple pie tasted okay. They have lost mine and my entire family's business.  I know these had to be different owners than the ones in the past.  The staff was all Asian, either Chinese or Japanese so perhaps they just do not know how to run an American restaurant.  Of course I love both Chinese and Japanese food but not when I expect American food in an American restaurant on an American Thanksgiving Day.  Thank you for allowing me to express my opinion and disappointment in this traditional meal that my family and I have enjoyed for years there in the past.

reviewText: I ordered four tacos to go, drove home and found my order made completely wrong. It was too far to go back and re-order.   Advice for any vegetarians wishing to dine here: *make sure* you say no meat, probably twice, instead of saying "I'd like only veg items x, y and z". Because they did give me x, y and z, only on top of a mountain of beef.  Other times, the food has been okay and the service isn't bad (at least at the counter). As a plus, they did charge me the 75 cents for a meatless taco. Could've been worse, could've been way better.

reviewText: Who doesn't love conveyor belt sushi? The Pacific NW is rife with these places. While Blue C is a charming venue with attentive staff (who have forgiven me a dish I disliked--why do sushi makers ever put mayo in rolls?), the sushi is hit or miss, sometimes sublime and velvety and of the highest quality, but one time I encountered some off fare that left me queazy as I sat watching a performance at ACT.

reviewText: Landed in Seattle and got settled into my hotel, then thought I would shoot over and check out Pike's Place Market.  Feeling hungry, not wanting to eat "counter" food and really wanting a glass of wine, I saw Pike Place Bar and Grill, it's right outside the market so there should be some great fish, right? Wrong.  The lunch menu hardly offers any fish selection at all, a sandwich and a salad with salmon.  So since I'm in the Pacific Northwest, the home to all the best salmon in the world, and it's so close to the market, I asked about the salmon and was told; no.  Not only is it not fresh local salmon, it's Atlantic salmon.  WTF?  So I ordered a French Dip Sandwich ($10.99) that had a bit of meat between bun and some soggy french fries.  I did get a mediocre indifferent glass of cabernet for $7.25; and it also was NOT from Washington.  Have you heard of local?  LindySez: I should have gone for the counter food in the market ...

reviewText: I was not much of a Thai fan until one of my coworkers made me go here.  Lunch is definately the way to go because you get huge overly generous portions, free soup, and a great eggroll to top it off.  Options 6 through 8 are traditional thai favorites.  Pad thai at #6 is enjoyed by most.  I personally like the Pud See Uk (sp?) or #8 as I call it.  I go here twice a week and was actually kind of upset when they closed for a holiday week because it has been such a staple for me.   Must try it once and a weekday lunch is my recommendation

reviewText: Hands down, the BEST Pizza in town !!!  Get the NY Style Pizza - they use fresh cheese, homemade sauce and delicious toppings. My favorite is actually the regular cheese pizza, but also try the pesto, white cheese, meatball.....and others. They are all delish!  You can also order by the slice or a whole pizza pie.  The cool chic - Lily is always working hard and delivers excellent customer service, every single time I'm there! And Andrea and the rest of the staff and owner are super friendly, treat you like family, and quick w/ service. Small family-owned businesses are the best.  Small cool restaurant.... and that's all you need.  Come in and try these guys out... you will not be disappointed.

reviewText: OMG... Burger Lounge is the Absolute BEST Burger joint in town!  I always get the yummy Lounge Burger w/ American Cheddar, lettuce, tomatoes, sauce, cooked medium.  And fresh french fries w/ ranch dressing. Yumm!  AND it's Grass-Fed Beef.  That's what beef is suppose to be - grass-fed, lean, delicious.  Everything is made "Fresh - Made To Order" !!!  They do not cook it, till you order it.  And that's what real food is suppose to be.  I also like the fact that their pop is organic w/ cane sweetened real sugar. That's what real pop is.   None of that processed corn syrup crap.  AND absolutely great customer service from Romel, dude who looks like Ed Norton, and the rest of the staff rocks!  They always make sure I'm completely satisfied, refill and bring over extras to make you happy.  The fresh local food, excellent customer service and great ambience and vibe, -- has made me a regular customer.  Thx Burger Lounge... You guys rock!

reviewText: We cannot say enough about how great our experience was at Sonoma Grille. We went there for the first time to celebrate our 2 year wedding anniversary. Upon learning this, they presented us with a complimentary champagne toast, followed by a complimentary dessert after dinner. Our server was very helpful in helping us select a wine. We are not big wine drinkers, so she allowed us to taste 3 different wines and we found one we really liked. Our server was very knowledgeable about the menu and provided great recommendations. The food was delicious, very reasonably priced, and perfectly portioned. We will definitely go back again for special occasions!

reviewText: A special evening out for my partner and I, the food was excellent - and hot! - and the attentiveness of our waiter was second-to-none. Would definitely recommend to friends and family to visit - I imagine booking over the weekends is essential, however!

reviewText: A popular haunt with the local student community, it's natural lighting makes for a more welcoming atmosphere than the other two nearby Wetherspoon venues (Brass Monkey or Gog and Ma'gog). On occasion they have ran out of the more popular food dishes. Generally a high standard of service and selection of food and local ales. Free WiFi through The Cloud (registration required) - though hit and miss in some areas of the venue. Outdoor area typically gets very busy in good weather. Only five minute walk from the main shopping area.

reviewText: I don't normally write reviews, but this place may warrant one... little slow and not extremely friendly when compared to the other nearby fast food joints. I even went the extra mile and checked the special online ahead of time.  But the price of my food was just about double and when questioned the employee stated I needed a coupon in order to honor the special.  I do not know if this is a problem with burger king on the larger scale or this particular franchise, but either way, I wasn't very impressed.

reviewText: I hit up Rudy's on a recommendation by the staff at the my hotel just down the road. Saying the food here is excellent is an understatement - it blew away my expectations about how BBQ should taste. The meat is tender and juicy - even the turkey! The cream corn is sinfully delicious. The decor is fun and up-beat, with a fantastic irreverent attitude that matches the energetic and engaged staff. Samples of the different options means you can make sure whatever you get is exactly what you want on the first try. My advice - this meat fills you up fast, 1/2 lb is all you need (however much your eyes are telling you to go for more).
name: Rudy's Country Store And Bar-B-Q

reviewText: Unbeatable superior service and some of the most flavourful foods yo'll ever taste!  You would never think it when driving by because the restaurant is hidden, but once you eat there, it'll become one of your favourite - if not your #1 place to dine!  Appetizers: Try the Shrimp Ajo and Spinach Salad Dinner: Salmon, Filet and Scallop dishes are delicious! Dessert: If you are a fan of chocolate mousse cake, then yo'll die for this one!  Is family-friendly + fine dining combined possible?!  YES!  Here, the owners love kids! They bring toys to the table, crayons and paper... They have sippy cups, plastic forks and spoons for toddlers - it's fantastic.

reviewText: When I walked in, at about 3 pm (definitely not "rush hour") I stood at the counter several minutes before any one acknowledged me. My husband and I ended up ordering two sandwiches. The Chicken Parm sandwich was good, but a little dry. The pastrami sandwich was delicious, the meat was tender and not too chewy. We also ordered a side of onion rings (which included about 10 onion rings for $3), and a bowl of the chili. The chili was good, though it tasted like it had green bell peppers in it, and that flavor was overpowering.    Like others have said, they only take cash, at the time of this review the ATM on the premise has a $2.00 fee. The staff was not very friendly, and not helpful. Perhaps because we were tourists, or because I'm not from Maine and am not used to what seems to be a common set-up in restaurants in this area (order at the front, then seat yourself).

reviewText: Let me start out with my warning: this is not the place to take a toddler. Though the staff was nice, it is a small neighborhood place with a very hushed, cozy atmosphere. The staff was quick to get us a high chair, but many of the patrons gave us disapproving looks as we buckled our 2 year old into the seat. She had one "outburst" that lasted less than a minute, then was her usual, quiet, self the entire time - but I felt like I was imposing on "their place".  Having been there, I don't think I would take my toddler there again. We found The Front Room through google search and chose to go there because of all the great reviews. The food was definitely good. I had the Reuben and my husband had the Croque Madame (ham and cheese sandwich with a fried egg on top). I tasted both and they were delicious. They were served with home-made bread and butter pickles - yumm! We ordered the "side" of oatmeal for our toddler, and it was a massive bowl, and it was also really tasty (the waitress gave us some sort of fruit preserves to add to it).   Overall it was delicious, and would be a great place to go with adults or older children, but the place is small and typically quiet - so out of courtesy to the other patrons I would not suggest taking younger children.

reviewText: It was horrible.   My husband and I spent our wedding anniversary at the Northville location. Our server, Jeremy, was inattentive.  There was a hair long, brown hair in my sangria. He nearly forgot to offer to replace it. Instead, he barely offered a half-cocked apology.   We didn't get bread until half-way through our meal.  We had to wave him down in  order to get new plates.  My husband ordered a chocolate silk pie. It was hard, the  crust was dry and crumbled off the "pie". It was obviously old.    Jeremy, rather than replacing the desert, laughed off our complaint. Tried to attribute it to "people taste as are different".  He basically said "sorry you don't like it" but didn't do anything to rectify the situation.   The food was not nearly as seasoned or as fresh as Texas De Brazil.   We spent nearly $150.00 for our meal and were treated like we were at some casual dining spot.   My husband's stomach was torn up an hour after leaving.  We will NEVER go there again. Never.

translated: This is the bulgogi  I have had in several years, it is the closest to traditional that i have seen in a while. They are very friendly. I showed up one day 15 minutes before they opened and they allowed me to come in and review the menu while they prepared for opening. The best part is I have never gotten sick from their food which tells me they take care in the way the food is prepared. I actually am going to get some now.

reviewText: Very poor service! We specifically ordered food, for our 7 year old, made a certain way. When we received it, it was not as we ordered. We waited 10 minutes....still waiter...no refills...oh and no tortillas for the fish fajitas that arrived 8 minutes prior to everyone eels food!!! Our other son ordered their Nachos...gross!!!!! So he ate our other son's messed up order. When our waiter finally decided to check on us, we told him about the situation. He said "well, I'm going to have to charge you for another burger!" As though WE were in the wrong! We were overcharged for the fish fajitas, the rest of the food was mediocre. The staff was RUDE and inattentive to our needs.
name: La Botana Mexican Restaurant

reviewText: I always enjoy dining at Mity Nice Grill because the staff is always so attentive and a friendly.  The sweet potato fries are to die for.  And, I feel that it is a great value for the price.  And let's not forget about the LEYE points!

reviewText: Expect around an hour of queuing on weekday evenings if you haven't booked - but it's well worth it. The layout is spacious, less cramped than Meat Liquor in the city and service is quick. The  Donkey Punch (served in a steel tumbler) and Game Over cocktails are both very potent but delicious. Try the garbage plate, bingo wings & monkey fingers to start, and one of the chili burgers if you have space left over.
name: MEATmission

reviewText: The BLT burger was one of the best I had in NY. On other occasions I had the Pastrami Reuben and the Ravioli which were both quite yummy too. Can't finish without a mention of the cocktails, Brian and Aleesha both do wonders with the booze.

reviewText: The "Flat Iron" is a little known cut of beef taken from the shoulder of the cow. You are greeted with popcorn and a jug of tap water. The steak isn't huge, and it comes with a small side salad, in a cute little glass tumbler. Given the size of the steak you will need two sides - don't miss the roast aubergine (other sides available are beef dripping chips & market greens). Wine is quite reasonable and is served in 1/2 pint glasses. The béarnaise sauce is really fantastic. The cocktail bar/ waiting area downstairs is pretty cool too, serving delicious doughnuts.  Tip: Don't nick the cleavers, however tempted you are!!
name: Flat Iron

reviewText: Went at lunch-time with a friend. Atleast 6 outside tables and 5 inside were vacant but we were told sternly by a very unfriendly waitress 'make up your mind where you want to sit -i won’t move you later.’ two diet cokes arrived 27 minutes after we ordered, starters alongside the mains in another 15 minutes. my risotto was overcooked and salty, my friend’s salmon pasta had too much oil and too many chillies (unlike the Prezzo in Greenwich). Overall a harrowing experience, I’ll stick to Zizzi next time!!

reviewText: We sat at the bar, overlooking the kitchens, so could see first-hand the love that went into preparing each course. Not being wine experts, we decided to go for the wine matching. The maître d' guided us through each wine (where its from, what year, why does it go well with this particular dish). On to the food, each course was a delight to the senses - with the chef who prepared it bringing to the table - then explaining how s/he cooked it.  The food/ wine combinations we had was as below (off http://restaurant-relae.dk/en/menuen/)  Hake, old leeks and salted Bergamot/ Quartz ’10 – Claude Courtois, Soings en Sologne.  Green asparagus, Sunflower seeds and Mint/ Bouchat ’10 – Guy Blanchard, Mâcon.  Chicken wings, White asparagus and Anchovies./ Panier de Fruits ’09 – La Coulée D’Ambrosia, Anjou.  Elderflower and Rhubarb./ Ҫava Bien ’11 – Philippe Bornard, Pupillin, Jura.  All in all, dining at Relæ was a sublime experience - I'm going back to Copenhagen just to dine here!
name: Relae

reviewText: Wonderful service, great food and lovely ambience. The manager allowed us to use TasteLondon cards even though we hadn't booked earlier - this was a Thursday night, so they were almost full. We ordered some Valpolicella, bread (a chunk of fresh bread & olives, garlic, malt vinegar). I had the Kobe Rump steak which was perfectly done, nice chunky (and not too oily) fries. The (special of the day) Salmon my friend ordered looked fresh. My other mate had Ostrich which he said was juicy and well seasoned. I had a Irish coffee to finish, it was just ok (not enough Whiskey?). Thanks to TasteLondon, I'm going to B&G again and again!

reviewText: Had a great time at Brasserie Toulouse Lautrec. For starters I had 6 burgundy snails in garlic butter (never had snails before) which were heavenly. Main was slow-cooked british pork belly with antillais black pudding, confit apple and truffle infused red wine sauce which was delicious though a bit underwhelming. For dessert (Homemade Apple Tart) we moved upstairs, adding jazz to the mix - it was a lovely evening overall.  Hint: The Wine List is extensive, almost all French (of course!) and very reasonable.

reviewText: Service at Kai is a bit tardy, but the food makes up for it! The roast duck was like none I've had before in London, the wasabi prawns had just the right amount of wasabi and the slow-cooked Egg with black truffle was cooked to perfection. The highlight of our meal though was "cài with 3 chillies" - a vegetarian(!) main our waiter recommended - triple fried tofu that was just out of this world.  Eating at Kai is likely to dent your wallet quite a bit - but it's well worth it. Very upmarket, very sophisticated and well deserving of it's Michelin star. The one thing this place lacks is a decent cocktail list - but the wine list is a-OK.

reviewText: Pedi para llevar un platillo por telefono, cuando llego me dan la cuenta y veo que viene un "extra" y pregunto de que es, me dice un señor muy serio que elos siempre cargan ese "extra en los platoa para llevar por el container donde ponen el platilo, los utensilios desechables, servilletas, etc.. y yo pongo mi carita de :? pago y antes se salir me dice, no se preocupe no le cargue el "extra" esta vez, cuando me dispongo a comer me doy cuenta que ni me cargo el "extra" ni mw puso utensilios o servilleta o sal, etc... ah! por el plato pague casi 16 dlls, estaba rico, si, pero conozco mejores restaurantes  con mejor calidad de servicio y a un precio razonable! translated: I asked to take a dish over the phone, when I arrive they give me the bill and I see that an "extra" is coming and I ask what it is, a very serious man tells me that they always load that "extra in the dishes to take to the container where They put the saucer, the disposable utensils, napkins, etc. and I put on my face: "I pay and before leaving he tells me, don't worry, don't charge him the "extra" this time, when I get ready to eat I realize They didn't charge me the "extra" nor did they put utensils or napkins or salt, etc... ah, I paid almost 16 dollars for the dish, it was delicious, yes, but I know better restaurants with better quality of service and at a reasonable price! I will definitely not eat there again!

reviewText: I've going to Cafe Shane for years and my experience just gets worse every time. I ordered my food then waited almost an additional 40 minutes for this guy to even comes close enough for me to ask for another water.  I had to ask to pay my bill before I walked out. Still no apology from anyone except the waitress who I  met before but was not serving me that day. The time before that there was another waitress who took our order then forgot to put in one of the orders then asked if we still wanted it.  Are you kidding me?  As much as I love the food, that was probably my last time there.

reviewText: I walked into the Chowder Pot for the first time on a Friday evening and was not even greeted with a hello, how many, or how can I help you from the hostesses.  I had to make the initial conversation at the hostess desk.  I was trying to ask a few questions about sitting at the bar and my responses were given to me in a short, nasty tone with absolutely no smile.  I felt as if I was bothering her and she did not want to help me.  The first 3 minutes at the Chowder Pot made me want to leave immediately.  Thankfully I had an amazingly wonderful waitress who made up for the hostess lack of friendly personality. The food was mediocre but delivered in a timely fashion.  I decided to stay in the bar/lounge area after dinner where yet again the servers were wonderful, friendly, had personality, and smiled (unlike the hostess).  Unfortunately my debit card was wrongfully charged and when I called Saturday morning to solve the problem the response I received was not very helpful, not apologetic, and yet again I felt as if I was bothering them as if it was my fault the mistake was made.  The people who actually work at Chowder Pot made the experience a great one, the hostess however needs to further her education in How to Have a Happy Personality and Smile as she is in the hospitality/customer service business.  I will not be returning to Chowder Pot.

reviewText: Wir sind hier auf Lehrgang und haben La Villa empfohlen bekommen. Die Locatioan an sich was für mich persönlich war nett aber bereits im Eingangbereich wurde klar das es nicht der sauberste Laden zu sein scheint. Mir viel sofort die Scharen an Mitarbeitern auf die vor der Eingangstür rauchten und uns auch keines Blickes würdigten. Ich sage gleich dazu das unsere Bedienung für den Abend TOP war.  Die Auswahl an Speisen von Buffet war überschaubar und auch in wirklich unansehnlichen Plastikschüsseln ala 90 Cent bei Aldi dargeboten.  Der Krautsalat war definitiv Fertigsalat so wie das meiste vom Buffet. Ich hatte Tintenfischringe, fitiert. Diese waren so hart, es spotet jeder Beschreibung.  Wir hatten auch das Rodizio. Die ersten zwei Gänge Fleisch waren in Ordnung. Aber was dann kam, ich kann mich meinen Vorrednern nur anschliessen. In meinen Augen das billigste und schlechteste Fleisch was man für Geld bekommen kann.  Fettig, zäh teils trocken und allein der Geruch hat mich zwar probieren lassen aber ich habe alles liegen lassen. Eine unglaubliche Verschwendung an Fleisch  und, ich kann es nicht anders beschreiben. EKELHAFT !  Eine der Bedienungen, welche nicht wirklich Hygienisch aussah, brachte immer wieder das Fleisch und bediente sich selber am Buffet aus den Schüsseln per Hand !  Definitiv nie wieder ! Was mir aufgefallen ist, dass der Laden voll war. Es scheint Menschen zu geben denen es schmeckt. Mir leider nicht
name: La Villa im Bamberger Haus
translated: We are on a course here and were recommended La Villa. The location itself was nice for me personally, but already in the entrance area it became clear that it didn't seem to be the cleanest shop. I immediately noticed the crowds of employees who were smoking in front of the entrance door and didn't even look at us. I'll just say that our service for the evening was TOP. The selection of dishes from the buffet was manageable and also presented in really unsightly plastic bowls for 90 cents at Aldi. The coleslaw was definitely ready-made salad like most of the buffet. I had squid rings, fit. These were so hard they defy description. We also had the Rodizio. The first two courses of meat were fine. But what happened next, I can only agree with the previous speakers. In my opinion the cheapest and worst meat you can get for money. Greasy, chewy, partly dry and the smell alone made me try it, but I left everything behind. An incredible waste of meat and, I can't describe it any other way. DISGUSTING ! One of the waitresses, who didn't really look hygienic, kept bringing the meat and helping herself from the bowls at the buffet by hand! Definitely never again! What I noticed was that the store was full. There seem to be people who like it. Unfortunately not for me

reviewText: DO NOT ORDER ONLINE! STAY AWAY! On Mother's Day I placed a large order online costing almost $80 at 5:19pm. Pick up time was 5:59. I arrived at the restaurant at 5:58 and called in for curb side pickup. I was told I could wait 10 minutes while they boiled pasta (thats right boil pasta) for one of my meals or I could order something that they could make faster. It takes 9 (NINE) minutes to cook noddles, if they need 10 minutes that means they have NOT started making the meal yet. While I waited I call back to speak to the manager who said a few things that really stuck out; "....ordering online does NOT reflect what we have in store." Also that they had used "my" pasta for another order. He did NOT offer anything for the inconvenience and would NOT cancel my order after I made multiple requests for him to do so. When the order came out I made the sever go back inside and get her manager. She came back with two men. One was the manager I had spoke with, the other had tattoos covering both arms said nothing and stood over me the whole time (don't complain the might beat you up lol). What a JOKE!(yes I mean him and the store) There were also two other employees sitting outside in front of my car watching the show! I opened all the orders only handling mine and my wife. My CF steak was cold and soggy. I made him give money back for the CF steak and the pasta which was the problem in the first place. When I finally returned home with the food my family was sorely disappointed with the quality and temperature of their meals. Most of the food was discard to the garage(where it belonged). WASTE OF TIME and MONEY! Not so much rude as flat out incompetent! BOB EVENS had NO intention of having my order completed on time, even tho they able to do so.

reviewText: I had been to this place a couple of times back when it was called the Pamir Kabob House and did not like it at all because it was filthy and the food was horrible.  Last Monday we just happened to go to the Worldgate Center for lunch and I noticed that the place looked different and had a different name, my friend and I decided to give it a try again and give them another chance so to speak.....  Boy.. were we surprised!, This place has done a 180 turn around from a year or so ago as far as the food and atmosphere, I have been to many Kabob Houses in the Northern Virginia and Maryland, but seen nothing like this. The cleanest, Classiest Mediterranean fast casual restaurant I have seen and the food was just out of this world.  The lunch Buffet consists of different kinds of salads, Soups, hummus,yogurt different rices, 5 or 6 different Kabobs ( Beef, Chicken,Lamb) and sides of lamb or chicken curry and other stews...and their fresh baked bread... just too many to mention and then the desert and watermelon and hot tea...we just felt like royalty for around $10... folks you pay more than that for a little salad and soup or hummus at other places. Everything was fresh and the kabobs were being served as soon as they were made.  I have to compliment the new owners and management for a fine job they have done to this place and hope that others will learn to give their customers such value and service.

reviewText: Don't bother, unkempt facility, marginal food and waitress ignored table.  Went here 2/19/14, snow birds visiting inlaws.  Place opened at 4:30 and was not busy. Despite that, we had no service until 5:05 when the waitress who was excessively busy doting over another table finally looked our way and said, "ooh, I didn't know I had your table, I didn't know I was assigned to the schmiddle", whatever the heck that means to me, I don't know or care .  Keep in mind, the regulars were already getting their meals by now.  Placed our drink order and went to wash up, found bathroom falling apart, soap dispenser had fallen off the wall and was empty???  1/4" of dust observed on top of mirror frame as well as picture frames, wish I took a photo for you.  Wonder how well kept the kitchen is???  Came out of washroom to  find our drink order had still not processed, that's going to be difficult to do without a bartender behind the bar?  Ordered chicken and eggplant parm, didn't get the eggplant part of it, so asked for my eggplant and I received 2 pieces of eggplant on a plate with no cheese on top, just some sauce, not too appetizing that way. Overall, meal was just ok, the chicken breast was not pounded, it was almost 3/4" thick, not the way chicken parm is supposed to be.  Wife did not enjoy her lemon chicken much either, kind of slimy she said and pasta overcooked.  Won't go back here next year.  Told inlaws to steer clear.

reviewText: Had a couple of really bad experiences with service at this Red Robin location. My wife and I are older and due to dietary restrictions going out a getting a burger at Red Robin is a treat for us. The waiter arrived at our table fairly promptly and our order arrived fresh and hot, the fries ( my favorite ) being excellent, crispy and hot. The waiter returned once more refreshing my soft drink, after that we never saw him again. We ate our burgers and fries and then sat there for 15 - 20 minutes looking for the server to ask for more fries and were going to order a bit of dessert. We felt like we had suddenly become invisible. My wife left the table for a bit and I gathered the serving dishes and utensils together and piled everything up on the table and stood up. Finally the manager walked over and asked if we were looking for our server. Needless to say I wasn't exactly happy by this time. What had started as an evening for a small treat, ended as a miserable experience. This was the second time that something like this has happened to my wife and I at this location. It will be the last! As much as I like Red Robin burgers they will no longer receive my business. The other closest location is too far of a drive just to get a burger. I do need to add that the manager did cancel the meal ticket and apologized, but the damage has been done. Having this happen twice is the clincher, no reason to go for the third time. I have a small business and usually purchase a couple of hundred dollars in Red Robin gift certificates as stocking stuffers for employees during Christmas every year. That won't happen any more either. Too many other restaurants that are willing to give better service than this one.
name: Red Robin Gourmet Burgers
address: ['317 Mid Rivers Mall Dr', 'St Peters, MO 63376']

reviewText: I have NEVER written a review on anything and never thought I would but I had to because of the worst restaurant experience I've had in my entire life thanks to Keke's!! Keke's is an overpriced Denny's, I have talked to many people since my experience and they ALL agree. I eat out 5-7 days a week for breakfast lunch and dinner so I definitely have enough experience to known what is good and what isn't. The worst part of the entire restaurant is the management! The service was ok at best, the food took an hour to come out (which was completely wrong when it did), the food is also just ok (it's breakfast how hard is it!!), and last but most important is when the manager came to the table (after I asked for him) he just said "sorry", literally that is ALL he said, needless to say we paid the tab (without eating) and walked out! I would like to sum this review with two words that describes Keke's.......IT SUCKS!!!!

reviewText: If I were to come to Melting Pot and do it all over again I would just come for the dessert. Their food isnt that good, and because you cook your own food for the entree if you are doing it with a group it gets really crowded cooking the food in that small pot. Plus the prices are ridiculously expensive for what you get. Trust me just go out to a different restaurant for dinner and then come here for a fun dessert by dipping yummy bite size desserts in amazing chocolate.  That is my advice when coming to this restaurant. Plus this restaurant could use a make over. The carpets need to be redone, there were holes in different places, the booths are very uncomfortable. So sitting there for 2 1/2 hours dipping your food isnt exactly relaxing.

reviewText: This is by far the best place to get sushi and any other genuine Japanese cuisine.  This place is owned by a husband and wife who have been cooking and making sushi for YEARS!  They are so nice.  They will make your food to your specifications. The service is great!  And most of all, the best food around!  My favorite dishes are the spicy tuna roll (he makes his own spicy sauce made from hot peppers and other spices...it is soo hot, but I cannot have sushi without it!) The teriyaki chicken is phenomenal, the beef tetaki is also fantastic...The vegetables are always fresh, the meat is always tender and seasoned to perfection, they always give you the best fruit after your meal...sometimes complimentary.  I honestly cannot say enough about this place.  It may not look very inviting from the outside, but I promise...you will have a great dining experience here.  I have turned so many people into Akashi fans and sushi lovers by taking them here.  I have been coming here for 6 years or more and will continue to be a proud patron.
name: Akashi Japanese Restaurant

reviewText: This is easily my #1 go-to spot in Falls Church for hangin' and good eats. Why you ask?  The food is excellent here - I've never had a bad meal and I've been coming here for years. My faves are the fish and chips, fried pickles and the burritos.  The prices on beers and food is friendly.  The atmosphere is fun, relaxed and casual - exactly what yo're expecting from a place called the Beach Shack. The tunes are chill (usually a mix of reggae and rock and roll), and the beachy decor puts you in the right frame of mind for hanging with your buds over some brews and good times.   In the summer, this is the place to be, listening to a live band outside in the (very large) patio area.   The service is always A+ - food is served right on time and the management and staff are always on it - high-five.  The clientele is... everybody! Yo'll be rubbing elbows with State Theater goers, families, hipsters, hotties, neighbors, friends, etc. If they live in Falls Church, yo'll find them at the Beach Shack (sooner or later).  See you there!

reviewText: Good not great but worth a try.  Decor was nice, nothing was dusty like another reviewer mentioned.  The server was prompt but not terribly affable.  The sweet green salsa was very good, the red salsa was not to our liking.  I really liked the charred outer skin of the sweet onion ball, but as I got to the center it was more like eating a savory cooked apple; not bad but not wonderful.  Almost everything we tried mixed sweet with another flavor.  Sometimes it worked and other times it didn't.  If you go in expecting something like Cafe Rio or Bajios you will be disappointed, prices are higher, portions are smaller and the flavors are not traditional mexican-american fast food.  But if you want something different it's worth giving it a try for yourself.
name: Milagros Mexican Restaurant

Almost everything we tried mixed sweet with another flavor.  Sometimes it worked and other times it didn't. reviewText: HGHLY RECOMMEND!  Excellent,from service to food to atmosphere. Visiting a friend in Paia, and we were supposed to hit a steakhouse in Makawao, but he runs on hawaii time and the place was closed.  Walked into Pollies  minutes shy of closing.  Waitress asked the cook and they stayed open for us.  Ordered a burger, thing was huge, bigger than any regualr restaurant. Also got chicken and beef tostados as an app.  Fresh made chips and great salsa to munch on while waiting.  We were stuffed and they gave us about a half pound of salsa and big bag of chips to go for free.  It is BYOB.  Quick Note, across the street is an italian restaurant Casanova's, on Wednesday nights it is Ladies Night, not my scene, but had a great time.  DJ, dance floor.

reviewText: Came to Maui, and after the jet lag sank in, I craved a slice of pizza like back home in Philadelphia.  I had been told that the flatbread pizza was OK, but nothing special.  I found Serpico's on google and it fit all the criteria.....no all organic, vegetarian, vegan, etc... items on the menu, reasonably priced, and BYOB.  Tasted just like home, includes free garlic bread w/sauce..  3 of us ate and including tip it was roughly $60. Calamari, pizza, salad, canoli's, drinks.  Wait staff was there when you needed anything.  Small place with a small bar and tables, Classic Mom & Pop pizzaria, but halfway up a Mountain in Paradise.  HIGHLY RECOMMEND!!

reviewText: So frustrating when you enjoy the food at a restaurant but the service makes you never want to go back again!  Our server disappeared for 15-20 minutes at a time on a regular basis, which baffled me especially when people at our table had just asked for menus to order more.  And we weren't there during busy "dinner hours"...we sat down at 8pm and the restaurant was 1/3 empty.  We had to ask other servers to go and find ours in the back multiple times, and when she did return she was not apologetic whatsoever but acted put-off.  Poor service really makes the meal feel overpriced.
name: Grillsmith
translated: So frustrating when you enjoy the food at a restaurant but the service makes you never want to go back again! reviewText: I love Tara Thai! My husband and I probably go to Tara about once a week, on average.  They have the best Happy Hour in the area, and they are awesome at making drinks.  The food is absolutely delicious!  I can't rave enough about the: Green Curry, Panang, Pattaya noodles, sea food madness, tom klong gong soup, and many more!   If you're there for happy hour, get the calamari!  The quality of the squid is top-notch, and the unique sauce is great!  The customer service is phenomenal, especially for regulars.  Everyone truly cares and wants the customer to have a good experience, and the manager is great.   My only minor complaint is that, personally, I like my thai food to be a little bit spicier than how they make it (but I'm a head-addict when it comes to food).. but I just ask for the spice tray and add more spice.. works perfectly!  Can't stress enough how yummy and enjoyable this place is!  My advice: Make this your "cheers bar" and eat up!

reviewText: Sea Pearl is amazing.  The decor is so elegant and well done.  It's certainly one of the prettiest restaurants around.  They are a little pricey, which is fair/understandable since the food is phenomenal and the decor is so lovely.  If you still want the experience, but yo're watching your budget.. hit up Happy Hour!  They have a cute lounge and really affordable specials... $4 sushi rolls (generous portions) and $1 oysters... their calamari is great and their mussels are the best I've ever had. The sushi is the best tasting I've ever eaten, also.  I DEFINITELY recommend the rainbow roll.  Their sea food is amazing, though I've never tried the meat/poultry.  Only complaint: their mixed drinks have been weak every time I've gotten one, which is a personal pet peeve of mine.. No one wants to pay top dollar for a glass full of club soda!   suggestion: If you can, go after dark when the place lights up.. that's when the decor is the most striking!

reviewText: My friend and I were stuck in Jacksonville due to a delayed flight and were lucky enough to find this gem. The food was amazing! Don't miss the brown butter, squash, sage, raviolis with duck confit. The specials and desserts were fantastic as well. Our server Camille was pleasant, helpful and charming. The only thing I was not fond of at this establishment was the Kenny G-esque music being pumped throughout. If/when ever in Jacksonville again I will return to Black Sheep, especially to check out their roof top, which we learned about from some friendly diners at the table next to us.

reviewText: There new men features a variety of beef dips! My son picked the style (D6) that adds bacon and jalapeño jack cheese - "Really?"...YUP! And wow! Good quality beef, buttered/toasted bread, perfectly cooked bacon (crispy on the edges, and chewy on the middle - nice 1/8" thickness), and a healthy portion of dipping au jus. We asked them to split the 8" and they happily provided two platters & two pickles! Really good experience!
